# Mobile App

This directory is the home for your iOS app. A workspace has been pre-created at the repo
root — open **`{{ swift_project_name }}.xcworkspace`** in Xcode to get started.

## Create the Xcode Project

> **Open the workspace first.** The "Add to" dropdown in the save dialog only appears when a
> workspace is already open. If you start from File → New → Project without opening the workspace
> first, you'll get a standalone project instead.

1. Open **`{{ swift_project_name }}.xcworkspace`** (at the repo root) in Xcode
2. **File → New → Project**, choose **App** under **iOS** (see note below on iOS vs Multiplatform)
3. Set the product name to **`{{ swift_project_name }}`**, then click Next
4. In the save dialog, before clicking Create:
   - Navigate the file picker into **`apps/ios/`** — Xcode defaults to the workspace directory, so you must manually navigate one level deeper
   - Set **Add to:** `{{ swift_project_name }}` — pick the workspace entry (the one with the workspace icon, not the `{{ project_name }}` folder)
   - Set **Group:** `{{ swift_project_name }}` — same workspace entry, same icon. **Do not pick the `{{ project_name }}` folder** — using the folder here breaks the workspace integration
   - Uncheck **Create Git repository** ← one already exists
5. Click **Create**

When done, the Project Navigator will show `{{ swift_project_name }}` as a collapsible item with
your source files, targets, and build settings underneath it — not just a flat file tree.

Always open Xcode via the workspace going forward, not the `.xcodeproj` directly.

> **iOS vs Multiplatform:** Choose **iOS**. It supports iPhone, iPad, Mac (Designed for iPad),
> and visionOS from a single target — just add destinations in project settings. The Multiplatform
> template creates separate Mac and iOS targets with divergent code paths, which is only needed
> for a fully native Mac app experience.

> **Already created the project?** Drag `apps/ios/{{ swift_project_name }}.xcodeproj` from
> Finder into the Project Navigator pane (look for the blue insertion indicator), or right-click
> in the Project Navigator and choose **Add Files to "{{ swift_project_name }}"**.

## Connect to the API

The Hono REST API runs at `http://localhost:3001/api` (start it with `pnpm start`).

An **OpenAPI 3.0 spec** is served at:
```
http://localhost:3001/api/openapi.json
```

Use [Swift OpenAPI Generator](https://github.com/apple/swift-openapi-generator) to generate a
type-safe Swift client automatically from this spec:

1. In Xcode, add via **File → Add Package Dependencies**:
   - `https://github.com/apple/swift-openapi-generator` — build plugin
   - `https://github.com/apple/swift-openapi-runtime` — runtime
   - `https://github.com/apple/swift-openapi-urlsession` — URLSession transport
2. Export the spec while the API is running:
   ```bash
   pnpm --filter {{ scope }}/api openapi:export > apps/ios/openapi.json
   # or
   curl http://localhost:3001/api/openapi.json -o apps/ios/openapi.json
   ```
3. Add `openapi.json` + the pre-staged `openapi-generator-config.yaml` to your app target
4. The generator runs at build time — Xcode produces a type-safe `Client` you use directly

See the [Swift OpenAPI Generator docs](https://swiftpackageindex.com/apple/swift-openapi-generator/documentation)
for the complete setup guide.

## API Reference

| Method | Path | Description |
|--------|------|-------------|
| `GET` | `/api/health` | Health check |
| `GET` | `/api/users` | List users |
| `POST` | `/api/users` | Create user (`{ email, name? }`) |
| `GET` | `/api/openapi.json` | OpenAPI 3.0 spec |

All JSON responses use `snake_case` keys. Use `JSONDecoder.keyDecodingStrategy = .convertFromSnakeCase`
in your Swift client.
